# migrated from tests/cases/analogy.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test analogy]
# gen102 (L11): structural analogy "A is to B as C is to ?". The answer is NOT
# stored anywhere — it is DERIVED from a binary relation the KB holds. The
# relations are taught in ordinary form ("X is the capital of Y" -> capital(X,Y));
# the analogy then transfers to a held-out pair the system was never given.

> rome is the capital of italy
< Learned: capital(rome, italy).
> paris is the capital of france
< Learned: capital(paris, france).

# Forward: find capital(rome, italy), then resolve capital(paris, ?) -> france.
> rome is to italy as paris is to what?
< france.
# The proof is real — it cites the two relations the analogy stands on.
> how do you know?
< Because capital(rome, italy) holds, and capital(paris, france) — so france.

# Reverse direction: the SAME relation read the other way. italy:rome :: france:?
# resolves capital(?, france) -> paris. Structural, not a memorized pair.
> italy is to rome as france is to what?
< paris.

# Honest miss: the analogy SHAPE is recognized, the relation is found, but the
# fourth term is unknown — say exactly that instead of guessing or echoing.
> rome is to italy as berlin is to what?
< rome and italy are related by capital, but I don't know that relation for berlin.
